      "Agentic commerce, where an AI agent completes a purchase on a user's behalf, moved from conference demo to shipping infrastructure across late 2025 and into 2026, and the payment networks built the rails. Mastercard announced Agent Pay on April 29, 2025, introducing Agentic Tokens that bind a tokenized card credential to a specific agent, merchant scope, and consent policy, so a model like ChatGPT or Microsoft Copilot can check out without ever touching the raw card number. Launch partners included Microsoft, IBM, and Braintree. The proof point that matters for risk officers came in January 2026, when Mastercard completed a live AI-agent payment with Santander inside a regulated banking environment, and the network extended the program with Agent Pay for Machines in June 2026.",
      "The competitive structure is three overlapping protocols, not one standard. Visa's Trusted Agent Protocol, announced September 2025, centers on a Visa-issued Verified Agent ID paired with a separate consent record signed by the consumer's own issuing bank, putting the issuer in the trust loop. Google released AP2 in September 2025 with more than 60 launch partners, among them Mastercard, American Express, PayPal, Coinbase, and Salesforce, and built it with PayPal for the payment step. The strategic question for any platform is interoperability: a fragmented set of agent-payment standards recreates the same friction tokenization was supposed to remove.",
      "PayPal has positioned itself as the connective tissue. It adopted the Agentic Commerce Protocol to embed payments directly inside ChatGPT, letting users buy without leaving the conversation, and its tokens now interoperate with Mastercard's agentic framework, knitting two large networks together for AI-driven transactions. The design pattern across all of these is consistent: a verified agent identity, a cryptographically scoped token, and an explicit, auditable consent record. That triad is what lets a bank or merchant accept an agent-initiated payment without inheriting unbounded fraud liability.",
